Demonstration of single cell data processing on the brain data

We assume the following executable files are properly installed:

  • mmutil_filter_row

  • mmutil_spectral_cluster_col

Preprocessing

Create a working directory:

[ -d example/brain_2018-05-03/ ] || mkdir -p example/brain_2018-05-03/

Select top 5000 most variable features

if ! [ -f example/brain_2018-05-03/top.mtx.gz ]; then
    mmutil_filter_row 5000 \
    data/brain_2018-05-03/filtered_count_matrix.mtx.gz \
    data/brain_2018-05-03/features.tsv.gz \
    example/brain_2018-05-03/top \
    2> /dev/null
fi

# just copy the barcode file to be consistent
if ! [ -f example/brain_2018-05-03/top.barcodes.tsv.gz ]; then
    cp data/brain_2018-05-03/barcodes.tsv.gz example/brain_2018-05-03/top.barcodes.tsv.gz
fi

Show the full spectrum of the feature scores:

out.dir = "example/brain_2018-05-03/"

var.scores = out.dir %&% "top.full_scores.gz" %>%
    read_tsv(col_names="var", col_types="d") %>%
    mutate(idx = 1:n())

.gg.plot(var.scores, aes(x=idx, y=log(1 + var))) +
    geom_vline(xintercept=5000, lty=2, col='red') +
    geom_line(size=2) +
    ylab("log(1 + variance)") +
    xlab("ranked features")

Run clustering

Meta data to compare with the previous annotations:

meta.file = "data/brain_2018-05-03/filtered_column_metadata.txt"
meta.tab = fread(meta.file)

Let’s visualize clustering results with the following function:

.show.scatter = function(.argmax, .embed) {

    argmax.tab = fread(.argmax) %>%
        (function(x) { colnames(x) = c("TAG", "k"); x })

    embedded.tab = fread(.embed) %>%
        (function(x) { colnames(x) = c("e1", "e2"); x })

    ## Show 2D embedding of those clusters of cells

    .K = max(argmax.tab$k)
    .lab = c("cluster" %&% 1:.K, "unassigned")

    argmax.tab = argmax.tab[, k := factor(k, c(1:.K, -1), .lab)]

    .dt = cbind(argmax.tab, embedded.tab) %>% na.omit()

    p1 =
        .gg.plot(.dt, aes(x=e1, y=e2, color=as.factor(k))) +
        geom_point(size=.5)

    print(p1)

    ## Remove outlier cells
    .dt2 = merge(.dt, meta.tab, by = "TAG")[k != "unassigned"]

    p2 =
        .gg.plot(.dt2, aes(x=e1, y=e2, color=broad.cell.type)) +
        geom_point(size=.5)

    print(p2)
}

Gaussian Mixture Model after spectral transformation

if ! [ -f example/brain_2018-05-03/gmm.argmax.gz ]; then
    mmutil_spectral_cluster_col --mtx example/brain_2018-05-03/top.mtx.gz \
                                --method GMM --trunc 10 --verbose --rank 5 \
                                --col example/brain_2018-05-03/top.barcodes.tsv.gz \
                                --out example/brain_2018-05-03/gmm 2> /dev/null
fi

Density-based spectral clustering

A strong distributional assumption of underlying data often result in poor clustering results while density-based non-parametric clustering methods robustly identify clusters of data points distributed in an arbitrary fashion.

if ! [ -f example/brain_2018-05-03/dbscan_level_1.argmax.gz ]; then
    mmutil_spectral_cluster_col --mtx example/brain_2018-05-03/top.mtx.gz --rank 5 \
                                --method DBSCAN --knn 50 --prune_knn --min_size 50 --verbose \
                                --col example/brain_2018-05-03/top.barcodes.tsv.gz \
                                --out example/brain_2018-05-03/dbscan 2> /dev/null
fi
